{
  "text": "The language finiteness problem was first attacked in [CITATION_1] (for safe HORSes only), but their algorithm turned out to be incorrect [CITATION_2] . To our knowledge, the only known solution of this problem follows from a recent decidability result for the diagonal problem [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . This problem asks, given a nondeterministic HORS and a set of letters \u03a3, whether for every n \u2208 N the HORS generates a finite tree in which every letter from \u03a3 appears at least n times. Clearly, a nondeterministic HORS generates arbitrarily large trees exactly when for some letter a it generates trees having arbitrarily many a letters, i.e., when the answer to the diagonal problem for \u03a3 = {a} is \"yes\".",
  "citation_candidates": [
